              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Evolution Of SWCCG And How To Keep Up</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=822"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=822"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=1625">Derek "UnknownGlyph" Tessier</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 1625 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Looks at the game style and how it changed and how to keep ahead of the game.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Well since the start of SWCCG the game has changed and evolved.  It grew from a single set of 300+ cards to 8 sets and over 1800+ cards.  Styles and game strategies have also grown as the sets appeared.  A smart player is the one bringing back the old ideas or coming up with new ones all the time and catches many opponents off guard.<br>
<br>
It seemed that a new 'strategy' was brought to light with each new set.  A New Hope brought about the first capturing cards and epic events.	Hoth brought combat vehicles and shielded sites.  Dagobah brought about training, asteroids and big blue for the dark side.  Cloud City enhanced and boosted the power/need to capture and increased the big drain and battling.  Jabba's Palace brought about the use on non-unique aliens and a return to the ever growing planet of tatooine.  Special Edition brought objectives, operatives and the vehichle/starship swarm.  Endor brought back the battling and slowed up the force draining as well as countering some popular card abuses.  Reflections just brought all these sets together letting the 'old' and 'new' mix.<br>
<br>
Now it seems that the diversity of decks has increased to the point that preparing to fight against a certain deck type has become impossible to do.  Now it's just basically build your deckto counter the popular battling techniques and draining not knocking out the main theme of decks.  Sure there are single cards that can do huge damage to some themes but ways around these cards are coming into popularity.  With less emphasis on countering a complete deck theme.  Sense, Alter, Control came and went. Reacting and hiding from battles was out and is now in.  A viscious cycle of what to play and what to expect is always the major dillema.<br>
<br>
It's would seem the best way to find out the 'new' play style is to wait until you face it.	But can you not be the person to introduce the 'new' strat?  Or maybe bring back an old one to bite back into style.<br>
<br>
The easiest way to keep ahead of the majority of the competition is to not get stuck in a rut.	Continually relying on the same strategy with the same basic cards:<br>
     For example; With reacts coming into style with react deploying and react moving it seems that stopping this would be the next step.  This made characters from Hoth (for LS) and characters from endor (for DS) become useful.  This also made people read cards and put sense back into their deck for it's alternative use.  But that's just the battling aspect of the game and only one part of it.  Adding many battle destiny is in style but decks are starting to put in counters and the counters are becoming 'staple' cards in many decks now because of this.  Soon the counters will make destiny adders less useful so more power or more weapons included may become the new popular strategy.  Or perhaps character weapons and reducing the forfeit to zero will become a continuous occurance.  So first aid/sacrifice or just plain Blaster Deflection and Force Field will soon make the weapons less useful.<br>
<br>
With this website so easy to access it's pretty easy for all players, even those not able to be in tournament every month, to keep up with the times.	Using this resource to find the hot theme is the greatest asset to your deck construction.  Deciding if it's time to counter this hot theme or adapt it to your own deck is entirely up to your play style but be prepared for the counters to come about in the near future after you do well.  The safest bet is to counter the new theme and either bring back an old theme or adapt a current theme but change it slightly away from the expected.  A good example of this is the current no flip Hidden Base decks that use the objective to fool their opponenent then they play some planet sites/mains and drain battle you away.  Another example is the no flip Court Of The Vile Gangster...just battle and cause the free damage for a non-participating opponent.  But these are only examples for objective cards.  Dueling without the epic duel and big spread drain is slowly popping up.<br>
<br>
Finding the hot themes is the easier thing to do.  Coming up with a new strat/style or the 'perfect' counter to the hot theme is challenging.  This pretty much requires great familiarity with the cards and their uses, also good knowledge of current errata's and ruling.  But if your familiarity with the cards isn't memorization, take an hour or two and look through your cards yourself.  You may see a new idea or theme pop up from a little used card from an old set or perhaps you find that perfect counter to a popular combo.  The more effort you put into knowing the cards in the SWCCG universe the easier it is to play/create/counter a theme or strategy.<br>
<br>
So in conclusion: 1) Find out what the new theme/strategy is.  2)  Choose to either adapt it or counter it.  3)  Search for the cards best suited to counter the popular theme/strat.  4) Choose the cards to best abuse the theme you adapted or improve the power of your new theme.	5) Know the cards you play with and know the cards you don't play with.  6)  Remember always run forward when the ground is collapsing behind you.<br>
<br>
Glyph<br>
<br>
<br>
For great example of an old style coming back to haunt us.  Matt's You Ain't Activating Jack deck, a perfect example of an old school theme.	Very old school.  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=822"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=822"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=822" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
